# Data Fetching Conventions

## Use native `fetch` only

Do not add axios, React Query, or SWR. Use the browser's `fetch` API.

## `useEffect` with inner async function

Never make `useEffect` itself `async`. Declare an inner `async function` and call it:

```jsx
// ✅ GOOD
useEffect(() => {
  async function fetchData() {
    const response = await fetch(url);
    const result = await response.json();
    setData(result);
  }
  fetchData();
}, [dependency]);

// ❌ BAD
useEffect(async () => {
  const result = await fetch(url);
}, []);
```

## Standard headers

Always include `Content-Type` for JSON requests. Add `authorization` for authenticated endpoints:

```js
// Public request
headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json" }

// Authenticated request
headers: {
  "Content-Type": "application/json",
  "authorization": `Bearer ${localStorage?.token}`
}
```

## Form submission pattern

```jsx
// ✅ GOOD
async function handleSubmit(e, url, { field1, field2, setResponseType, setResponseData }) {
  e.preventDefault();
  const response = await fetch(url, {
    method: "POST",
    headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json" },
    body: JSON.stringify({ field1, field2 }),
  });
  const result = await response.json();
  setResponseType(response.status);
  setResponseData(result);
}
```

## Extract shared fetch logic into `utils.jsx`

Utility functions that wrap fetch calls or handle auth responses belong in `src/utils.jsx`. They receive state setters as **object-destructured parameters**:

```js
// ✅ GOOD
function handleAuthResponse({ result, setIsAuth, setUser, user, isAuth }) { ... }

// ❌ BAD — positional arguments are harder to call and extend
function handleAuthResponse(result, setIsAuth, setUser, user, isAuth) { ... }
```

## Displaying API errors

The API returns errors as an array. Check the status code, then map over the array:

```jsx
{responseData && responseType >= 400 && (
  <ul>
    {responseData.map((error, index) => (
      <li key={index} className="bg-red-200 text-red-800 px-3 py-1 rounded-lg">
        {error.msg}
      </li>
    ))}
  </ul>
)}
```
